# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: database-partitioning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:database-partitioning/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] In computer data storage, **data striping** is the technique of segmenting logically sequential data, such as a file, so that consecutive segments are stored on different physical storage devices.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Striping is useful when a processing device requests data more quickly than a single storage device can provide it.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] By spreading segments across multiple devices which can be accessed concurrently, total data throughput is increased.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] It is also a useful method for balancing I/O load across an array of disks.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Striping is used across disk drives in redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage, network interface controllers, disk arrays, different computers in clustered file systems and grid-oriented storage, and RAM in some systems.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] One method of striping is done by interleaving sequential segments on storage devices in a round-robin fashion from the beginning of the data sequence.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] This works well for streaming data, but subsequent random accesses will require knowledge of which device contains the data.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] If the data is stored such that the physical address of each data segment is assigned a one-to-one mapping to a particular device, the device to access each segment requested can be calculated from the address without knowing the offset of the data within the full sequence.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Other methods might be employed in which sequential segments are not stored on sequential devices.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Such non-sequential interleaving can have benefits in some error correction schemes.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Advantages of striping include performance and throughput.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Sequential time interleaving of data accesses allows the lesser data access throughput of each storage devices to be cumulatively multiplied by the number of storage devices employed.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Increased throughput allows the data processing device to continue its work without interruption, and thereby finish its procedures more quickly.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] This is manifested in improved performance of the data processing.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Because different segments of data are kept on different storage devices, the failure of one device causes the corruption of the full data sequence.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] In effect, the failure rate of the array of storage devices is equal to the sum of the failure rate of each storage device.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] This disadvantage of striping can be overcome by the storage of redundant information, such as parity, for the purpose of error correction.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] In such a system, the disadvantage is overcome at the cost of requiring extra storage.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] The segments of sequential data written to or read from a disk before the operation continues on the next disk are usually called *chunks*, *strides* or *stripe units*, while their logical groups forming single striped operations are called *strips* or *stripes*.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] The amount of data in one chunk (stripe unit), often denominated in bytes, is variously referred to as the *chunk size*, *stride size*, *stripe size*, *stripe depth* or *stripe length*.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] The number of data disks in the array is sometimes called the *stripe width*, but it may also refer to the amount of data within a stripe.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] The amount of data in one stripe multiplied by the number of data disks in the array (i.e., *stripe depth* times *stripe width*, which in the geometrical analogy would yield an area) is sometimes called the *stripe size* or *stripe width*.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] *Wide striping* occurs when chunks of data are spread across multiple arrays, possibly all the drives in the system.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] *Narrow striping* occurs when the chunks of data are spread across the drives in a single array.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Data striping is used in some databases, such as Sybase, and in certain RAID devices under software or hardware control, such as IBM's 9394 RAMAC Array subsystem.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] File systems of clusters also use striping.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Oracle Automatic Storage Management allows ASM files to be either coarse or fine striped.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] , failure of a single member drive of the RAID array causes all stored data to be lost.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] , if one member drive fails the data can be restored using the other drives in the array.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] The LVM system allows for the adjustment of coarseness of the striping pattern.
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] LVM has other advantages that are not directly related to data striping (like snapshots, dynamic resizing, etc).
[src:database-partitioning/data-striping] Have RAID like features but with the security of chunk integrity to detect bad blocks, and the added flexibility of adding arbitrary numbers of extra drives.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] PostgreSQL supports basic table partitioning.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This section describes why and how to implement partitioning as part of your database design.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Partitioning refers to splitting what is logically one large table into smaller physical pieces.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] These benefits will normally be worthwhile only when a table would otherwise be very large.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The exact point at which a table will benefit from partitioning depends on the application, although a rule of thumb is that the size of the table should exceed the physical memory of the database server.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The table is partitioned into “ranges” defined by a key column or set of columns, with no overlap between the ranges of values assigned to different partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For example, one might partition by date ranges, or by ranges of identifiers for particular business objects.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Each range's bounds are understood as being inclusive at the lower end and exclusive at the upper end.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For example, if one partition's range is from `1` to `10`, and the next one's range is from `10` to `20`, then value `10` belongs to the second partition not the first.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The table is partitioned by explicitly listing which key value(s) appear in each partition.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The table is partitioned by specifying a modulus and a remainder for each partition.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Each partition will hold the rows for which the hash value of the partition key divided by the specified modulus will produce the specified remainder.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If your application needs to use other forms of partitioning not listed above, alternative methods such as inheritance and `UNION ALL` views can be used instead.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Such methods offer flexibility but do not have some of the performance benefits of built-in declarative partitioning.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] PostgreSQL allows you to declare that a table is divided into partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The table that is divided is referred to as a *partitioned table*.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The declaration includes the *partitioning method* as described above, plus a list of columns or expressions to be used as the *partition key*.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The partitioned table itself is a “virtual” table having no storage of its own.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Instead, the storage belongs to *partitions*, which are otherwise-ordinary tables associated with the partitioned table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Each partition stores a subset of the data as defined by its *partition bounds*.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] All rows inserted into a partitioned table will be routed to the appropriate one of the partitions based on the values of the partition key column(s).
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Updating the partition key of a row will cause it to be moved into a different partition if it no longer satisfies the partition bounds of its original partition.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Partitions may themselves be defined as partitioned tables, resulting in *sub-partitioning*.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Although all partitions must have the same columns as their partitioned parent, partitions may have their own indexes, constraints and default values, distinct from those of other partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] See CREATE TABLE for more details on creating partitioned tables and partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] It is not possible to turn a regular table into a partitioned table or vice versa.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] However, it is possible to add an existing regular or partitioned table as a partition of a partitioned table, or remove a partition from a partitioned table turning it into a standalone table; this can simplify and speed up many maintenance processes.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] See ALTER TABLE to learn more about the `ATTACH PARTITION` and `DETACH PARTITION` sub-commands.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Partitions can also be foreign tables, although considerable care is needed because it is then the user's responsibility that the contents of the foreign table satisfy the partitioning rule.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] There are some other restrictions as well.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] See CREATE FOREIGN TABLE for more information.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Suppose we are constructing a database for a large ice cream company.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The company measures peak temperatures every day as well as ice cream sales in each region.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] We know that most queries will access just the last week's, month's or quarter's data, since the main use of this table will be to prepare online reports for management.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] To reduce the amount of old data that needs to be stored, we decide to keep only the most recent 3 years worth of data.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] At the beginning of each month we will remove the oldest month's data.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] In this situation we can use partitioning to help us meet all of our different requirements for the measurements table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Each partition's definition must specify bounds that correspond to the partitioning method and partition key of the parent.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Note that specifying bounds such that the new partition's values would overlap with those in one or more existing partitions will cause an error.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Partitions thus created are in every way normal PostgreSQL tables (or, possibly, foreign tables).
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] It is possible to specify a tablespace and storage parameters for each partition separately.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For our example, each partition should hold one month's worth of data, to match the requirement of deleting one month's data at a time.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Inserting data into the parent table that does not map to one of the existing partitions will cause an error; an appropriate partition must be added manually.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] It is not necessary to manually create table constraints describing the partition boundary conditions for partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Such constraints will be created automatically.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Create an index on the key column(s), as well as any other indexes you might want, on the partitioned table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] (The key index is not strictly necessary, but in most scenarios it is helpful.) This automatically creates a matching index on each partition, and any partitions you create or attach later will also have such an index.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] An index or unique constraint declared on a partitioned table is “virtual” in the same way that the partitioned table is: the actual data is in child indexes on the individual partition tables.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Ensure that the enable_partition_pruning configuration parameter is not disabled in `postgresql.conf`.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If it is, queries will not be optimized as desired.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] In the above example we would be creating a new partition each month, so it might be wise to write a script that generates the required DDL automatically.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Normally the set of partitions established when initially defining the table is not intended to remain static.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] It is common to want to remove partitions holding old data and periodically add new partitions for new data.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] One of the most important advantages of partitioning is precisely that it allows this otherwise painful task to be executed nearly instantaneously by manipulating the partition structure, rather than physically moving large amounts of data around.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This can very quickly delete millions of records because it doesn't have to individually delete every record.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Note however that the above command requires taking an `ACCESS EXCLUSIVE` lock on the parent table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Another option that is often preferable is to remove the partition from the partitioned table but retain access to it as a table in its own right.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] These allow further operations to be performed on the data before it is dropped.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For example, this is often a useful time to back up the data using `COPY`, pg_dump, or similar tools.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] It might also be a useful time to aggregate data into smaller formats, perform other data manipulations, or run reports.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The first form of the command requires an `ACCESS EXCLUSIVE` lock on the parent table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Adding the `CONCURRENTLY` qualifier as in the second form allows the detach operation to require only `SHARE UPDATE EXCLUSIVE` lock on the parent table, but see `ALTER TABLE ...
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] DETACH PARTITION` for details on the restrictions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Similarly we can add a new partition to handle new data.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] As an alternative to creating a new partition, it is sometimes more convenient to create a new table separate from the partition structure and attach it as a partition later.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This allows new data to be loaded, checked, and transformed prior to it appearing in the partitioned table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Moreover, the `ATTACH PARTITION` operation requires only a `SHARE UPDATE EXCLUSIVE` lock on the partitioned table rather than the `ACCESS EXCLUSIVE` lock required by `CREATE TABLE ...
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] PARTITION OF`, so it is more friendly to concurrent operations on the partitioned table; see `ALTER TABLE ...
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] ATTACH PARTITION` for additional details.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Note that when running the `ATTACH PARTITION` command, the table will be scanned to validate the partition constraint while holding an `ACCESS EXCLUSIVE` lock on that partition.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] As shown above, it is recommended to avoid this scan by creating a `CHECK` constraint matching the expected partition constraint on the table prior to attaching it.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Once the `ATTACH PARTITION` is complete, it is recommended to drop the now-redundant `CHECK` constraint.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If the table being attached is itself a partitioned table, then each of its sub-partitions will be recursively locked and scanned until either a suitable `CHECK` constraint is encountered or the leaf partitions are reached.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Similarly, if the partitioned table has a `DEFAULT` partition, it is recommended to create a `CHECK` constraint which excludes the to-be-attached partition's constraint.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If this is not done, the `DEFAULT` partition will be scanned to verify that it contains no records which should be located in the partition being attached.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This operation will be performed whilst holding an `ACCESS EXCLUSIVE` lock on the `DEFAULT` partition.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If the `DEFAULT` partition is itself a partitioned table, then each of its partitions will be recursively checked in the same way as the table being attached, as mentioned above.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] As mentioned earlier, it is possible to create indexes on partitioned tables so that they are applied automatically to the entire hierarchy.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This can be very convenient as not only will all existing partitions be indexed, but any future partitions will be as well.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] However, one limitation when creating new indexes on partitioned tables is that it is not possible to use the `CONCURRENTLY` qualifier, which could lead to long lock times.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] To avoid this, you can use `CREATE INDEX ON ONLY` the partitioned table, which creates the new index marked as invalid, preventing automatic application to existing partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Instead, indexes can then be created individually on each partition using `CONCURRENTLY` and *attached* to the partitioned index on the parent using `ALTER INDEX ...
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Once indexes for all the partitions are attached to the parent index, the parent index will be marked valid automatically.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This technique can be used with `UNIQUE` and `PRIMARY KEY` constraints too; the indexes are created implicitly when the constraint is created.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Individual partitions are linked to their partitioned table using inheritance behind-the-scenes.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] However, it is not possible to use all of the generic features of inheritance with declaratively partitioned tables or their partitions, as discussed below.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Notably, a partition cannot have any parents other than the partitioned table it is a partition of, nor can a table inherit from both a partitioned table and a regular table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] That means partitioned tables and their partitions never share an inheritance hierarchy with regular tables.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] While the built-in declarative partitioning is suitable for most common use cases, there are some circumstances where a more flexible approach may be useful.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This example builds a partitioning structure equivalent to the declarative partitioning example above.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Create several “child” tables that each inherit from the root table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Normally, these tables will not add any columns to the set inherited from the root.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Just as with declarative partitioning, these tables are in every way normal PostgreSQL tables (or foreign tables).
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Add non-overlapping table constraints to the child tables to define the allowed key values in each.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Typical examples would be: Ensure that the constraints guarantee that there is no overlap between the key values permitted in different child tables.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] A common mistake is to set up range constraints like: This is wrong since it is not clear which child table the key value 200 belongs in.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For each child table, create an index on the key column(s), as well as any other indexes you might want.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] We want our application to be able to say `INSERT INTO measurement ...` and have the data be redirected into the appropriate child table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] We can arrange that by attaching a suitable trigger function to the root table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If data will be added only to the latest child, we can use a very simple trigger function: After creating the function, we create a trigger which calls the trigger function: We must redefine the trigger function each month so that it always inserts into the current child table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The trigger definition does not need to be updated, however.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] We might want to insert data and have the server automatically locate the child table into which the row should be added.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] We could do this with a more complex trigger function, for example: The trigger definition is the same as before.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Note that each `IF` test must exactly match the `CHECK` constraint for its child table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] While this function is more complex than the single-month case, it doesn't need to be updated as often, since branches can be added in advance of being needed.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Note In practice, it might be best to check the newest child first, if most inserts go into that child.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For simplicity, we have shown the trigger's tests in the same order as in other parts of this example.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] A different approach to redirecting inserts into the appropriate child table is to set up rules, instead of a trigger, on the root table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For example: A rule has significantly more overhead than a trigger, but the overhead is paid once per query rather than once per row, so this method might be advantageous for bulk-insert situations.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] In most cases, however, the trigger method will offer better performance.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If you want to use `COPY` to insert data, you'll need to copy into the correct child table rather than directly into the root.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] `COPY` does fire triggers, so you can use it normally if you use the trigger approach.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Another disadvantage of the rule approach is that there is no simple way to force an error if the set of rules doesn't cover the insertion date; the data will silently go into the root table instead.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Ensure that the constraint_exclusion configuration parameter is not disabled in `postgresql.conf`; otherwise child tables may be accessed unnecessarily.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] As we can see, a complex table hierarchy could require a substantial amount of DDL.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] In the above example we would be creating a new child table each month, so it might be wise to write a script that generates the required DDL automatically.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Alternatively, one may want to create and populate the new child table before adding it to the table hierarchy.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] This could allow data to be loaded, checked, and transformed before being made visible to queries on the parent table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Without partition pruning, the above query would scan each of the partitions of the `measurement` table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] With partition pruning enabled, the planner will examine the definition of each partition and prove that the partition need not be scanned because it could not contain any rows meeting the query's `WHERE` clause.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] When the planner can prove this, it excludes (*prunes*) the partition from the query plan.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] By using the EXPLAIN command and the enable_partition_pruning configuration parameter, it's possible to show the difference between a plan for which partitions have been pruned and one for which they have not.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Some or all of the partitions might use index scans instead of full-table sequential scans, but the point here is that there is no need to scan the older partitions at all to answer this query.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Note that partition pruning is driven only by the constraints defined implicitly by the partition keys, not by the presence of indexes.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Therefore it isn't necessary to define indexes on the key columns.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Whether an index needs to be created for a given partition depends on whether you expect that queries that scan the partition will generally scan a large part of the partition or just a small part.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] An index will be helpful in the latter case but not the former.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Partition pruning can be performed not only during the planning of a given query, but also during its execution.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Partition pruning can be disabled using the enable_partition_pruning setting.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Constraint exclusion works in a very similar way to partition pruning, except that it uses each table's `CHECK` constraints — which gives it its name — whereas partition pruning uses the table's partition bounds, which exist only in the case of declarative partitioning.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Another difference is that constraint exclusion is only applied at plan time; there is no attempt to remove partitions at execution time.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The default (and recommended) setting of constraint_exclusion is neither `on` nor `off`, but an intermediate setting called `partition`, which causes the technique to be applied only to queries that are likely to be working on inheritance partitioned tables.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The `on` setting causes the planner to examine `CHECK` constraints in all queries, even simple ones that are unlikely to benefit.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The choice of how to partition a table should be made carefully, as the performance of query planning and execution can be negatively affected by poor design.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] One of the most critical design decisions will be the column or columns by which you partition your data.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Often the best choice will be to partition by the column or set of columns which most commonly appear in `WHERE` clauses of queries being executed on the partitioned table.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] `WHERE` clauses that are compatible with the partition bound constraints can be used to prune unneeded partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] However, you may be forced into making other decisions by requirements for the `PRIMARY KEY` or a `UNIQUE` constraint.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Removal of unwanted data is also a factor to consider when planning your partitioning strategy.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] An entire partition can be detached fairly quickly, so it may be beneficial to design the partition strategy in such a way that all data to be removed at once is located in a single partition.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Choosing the target number of partitions that the table should be divided into is also a critical decision to make.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Not having enough partitions may mean that indexes remain too large and that data locality remains poor which could result in low cache hit ratios.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] However, dividing the table into too many partitions can also cause issues.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Too many partitions can mean longer query planning times and higher memory consumption during both query planning and execution, as further described below.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] When choosing how to partition your table, it's also important to consider what changes may occur in the future.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] For example, if you choose to have one partition per customer and you currently have a small number of large customers, consider the implications if in several years you instead find yourself with a large number of small customers.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] In this case, it may be better to choose to partition by `HASH` and choose a reasonable number of partitions rather than trying to partition by `LIST` and hoping that the number of customers does not increase beyond what it is practical to partition the data by.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Sub-partitioning can be useful to further divide partitions that are expected to become larger than other partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Another option is to use range partitioning with multiple columns in the partition key.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Either of these can easily lead to excessive numbers of partitions, so restraint is advisable.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] It is important to consider the overhead of partitioning during query planning and execution.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] The query planner is generally able to handle partition hierarchies with up to a few thousand partitions fairly well, provided that typical queries allow the query planner to prune all but a small number of partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Planning times become longer and memory consumption becomes higher when more partitions remain after the planner performs partition pruning.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Another reason to be concerned about having a large number of partitions is that the server's memory consumption may grow significantly over time, especially if many sessions touch large numbers of partitions.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] That's because each partition requires its metadata to be loaded into the local memory of each session that touches it.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] With data warehouse type workloads, it can make sense to use a larger number of partitions than with an OLTP type workload.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Generally, in data warehouses, query planning time is less of a concern as the majority of processing time is spent during query execution.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] With either of these two types of workload, it is important to make the right decisions early, as re-partitioning large quantities of data can be painfully slow.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Simulations of the intended workload are often beneficial for optimizing the partitioning strategy.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] Never just assume that more partitions are better than fewer partitions, nor vice-versa.
[src:database-partitioning/ddl-partitioning] If you see anything in the documentation that is not correct, does not match your experience with the particular feature or requires further clarification, please use this form to report a documentation issue.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:database-partitioning/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] A **partition** is a division of a logical database or its constituent elements into distinct independent parts.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Database partitioning refers to intentionally breaking a large database into smaller ones for scalability purposes, distinct from network partitions which are a type of network fault between nodes.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] In a partitioned database, each piece of data belongs to exactly one partition, effectively making each partition a small database of its own.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Database partitioning is normally done for manageability, performance or availability reasons, or for load balancing.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] It is popular in distributed database management systems, where each partition may be spread over multiple nodes, with users at the node performing local transactions on the partition.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] This increases performance for sites that have regular transactions involving certain views of data, whilst maintaining availability and security.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Partitioning enables distribution of datasets across multiple disks and query loads across multiple processors.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] For queries that operate on a single partition, each node executes queries independently on its local partition, enabling linear scaling of query throughput with additional nodes.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] More complex queries can be parallelized across multiple nodes, though this presents additional challenges.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Database partitioning emerged in the 1980s with systems like Teradata and NonStop SQL.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] The approach was later adopted by NoSQL databases and Hadoop-based data warehouses.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] While implementations vary between transactional and analytical workloads, the core principles of partitioning remain consistent across both use cases.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Partitioning is commonly implemented alongside replication, storing partition copies across multiple nodes.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Each record belongs to one partition but may exist on multiple nodes for fault tolerance.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] In leader-follower replication systems, nodes can simultaneously serve as leaders for some partitions and followers for others.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Partitioning aims to distribute data and query load evenly across nodes.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] With ideal distribution, system capacity scales linearly with added nodes—ten nodes should process ten times the data and throughput of a single node.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Uneven distribution, termed *skew*, reduces partitioning efficiency.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Partitions with excessive load are called *hot spots*.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Current high-end relational database management systems provide for different criteria to split the database.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] They take a *partitioning key* and assign a partition based on certain criteria.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] In any partitioning scheme, data is typically arranged so that each piece of data (record, row, or document) belongs to exactly one partition.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] While some databases support operations that span multiple partitions, this single-partition association is fundamental to the partitioning concept.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] The partitioning can be done by either building separate smaller databases (each with its own tables, indices, and transaction logs), or by splitting selected elements, for example just one table.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Horizontal partitioning involves putting different rows into different tables.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] For example, customers with ZIP codes less than 50000 are stored in CustomersEast, while customers with ZIP codes greater than or equal to 50000 are stored in CustomersWest.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] The two partition tables are then CustomersEast and CustomersWest, while a view with a union might be created over both of them to provide a complete view of all customers.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Vertical partitioning involves creating tables with fewer columns and using additional tables to store the remaining columns.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Generally, this practice is known as normalization.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] However, vertical partitioning extends further, and partitions columns even when already normalized.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] This type of partitioning is also called "row splitting", since rows get split by their columns, and might be performed explicitly or implicitly.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Distinct physical machines might be used to realize vertical partitioning: storing infrequently used or very wide columns, taking up a significant amount of memory, on a different machine, for example, is a method of vertical partitioning.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] A common form of vertical partitioning is to split static data from dynamic data, since the former is faster to access than the latter, particularly for a table where the dynamic data is not used as often as the static.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] Creating a view across the two newly created tables restores the original table with a performance penalty, but accessing the static data alone will show higher performance.
[src:database-partitioning/partition-database] A columnar database can be regarded as a database that has been vertically partitioned until each column is stored in its own table.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] A **database shard**, or simply a **shard**, is a horizontal partition of data within a database or search engine.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Each shard may be held on a separate database server instance in order to spread across multiple servers.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Some data in a database may remain present in all shards, while other data is stored in only one shard.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] In such cases, each shard acts as the single source for its subset of data.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] There are numerous advantages to the horizontal partitioning of data.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Since tables are divided and distributed into multiple servers, the total number of rows in each table in each database is reduced.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] This reduces index size, which generally improves search performance.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] A database shard can be placed on separate hardware, and multiple shards can be placed on multiple machines.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] This enables the distribution of a database across a large number of machines, which can significantly improve performance.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] In addition, if the database shard is based on some real-world segmentation of the data (e.g., European customers v.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] American customers) it may be possible to infer the appropriate shard membership easily and automatically, and to query only the relevant shard.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Although it has long been implemented through manual coding (especially where rows have an obvious grouping, as in the customer region example above), this approach is often inflexible.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] There is a desire to support sharding automatically, both in terms of adding code support for it, and for identifying candidates to be sharded separately.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Consistent hashing is a technique used in sharding to distribute large loads across multiple smaller services and servers.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Where distributed computing is used to separate load between multiple servers (either for performance or reliability reasons), a sharding approach may also be useful.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] In the 2010s, sharding of execution capacity, as well as the more traditional sharding of data, emerged as a potential approach to address performance and scalability challenges in blockchains.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Recent academic work has proposed protocols such as Cerberus to address cross-shard atomicity by braiding consensus across multiple shards, allowing transactions to affect multiple partitions simultaneously without requiring a global lock.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Horizontal partitioning splits one or more tables by row, usually within a *single* instance of a schema and a database server.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] It partitions the relevant table or tables in the same way, but does so across potentially *multiple* instances of the schema.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] An advantage is that the search load for the large partitioned table can be distributed across multiple servers (logical or physical), rather than only across multiple indexes on a same logical server.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Splitting shards across multiple isolated instances requires more than simple horizontal partitioning.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] The expected gains in efficiency would be reduced if querying the database required *multiple* instances to be accessed just to retrieve a simple dimension table.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Beyond partitioning, sharding therefore involves distributing large, partitionable tables across servers, while smaller tables are replicated in full on each server.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] This is also why sharding is related to a shared-nothing architecture—once sharded, each shard can reside in a separate logical schema instance, physical database server, data center, or geographic region.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is intended to minimize the need for cross-shard access by partitioning data across independent shards.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] This makes replication across multiple servers easier (simple horizontal partitioning does not).
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] It is also useful for worldwide distribution of applications, where communications links between data centers might otherwise become a bottleneck.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] There is also a requirement for some notification and replication mechanism between schema instances, so that unpartitioned tables remain as closely synchronized as the application requires.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] This is a complex architectural choice in sharded systems: approaches range from making these tables effectively read-only (with updates that are rare and batched), to dynamically replicated tables (at the cost of reducing some of the distribution benefits of sharding), and many options in between.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Sharding a database table before it has been optimized locally can introduce unnecessary complexity.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is generally recommended when other optimization strategies have proven insufficient.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] The added complexity of database sharding can result in several potential challenges.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Richard Garriott, creator of *Ultima Online*, recalled that the term originated during the production of the game, specifically in creating a self-regulating, virtual ecology system.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] Players were able to interact and harvest in-game resources via the internet, which disrupted the balance of the system.
[src:database-partitioning/shard-database-architecture] The feature was later removed after several months of testing.
